description:
Replace fs.promises.appendFile calls with persistent fs.createWriteStream for better performance while preserving category files.

Current problem: Each log entry triggers 3 separate appendFile calls (all.log, level.log, category.log), creating I/O contention.

Solution: Use persistent write streams with Node/Bun's built-in buffering:

```typescript
private fileStreams: Map<string, fs.WriteStream> = new Map()

private getOrCreateStream(filename: string): fs.WriteStream {
    if (!this.fileStreams.has(filename)) {
        const filepath = path.join(this.config.logsDir, filename)
        const stream = fs.createWriteStream(filepath, { flags: 'a' })
        this.fileStreams.set(filename, stream)
    }
    return this.fileStreams.get(filename)!
}

private appendToFile(filename: string, content: string): void {
    const stream = this.getOrCreateStream(filename)
    stream.write(content)  // Non-blocking, kernel handles buffering
}
```

Benefits:
- Non-blocking writes (kernel-level buffering)
- All category files preserved
- Reuses existing unused `fileHandles` property
- Bun fully compatible with fs.createWriteStream

Note: Need to handle stream cleanup in closeFileHandles() and on rotation.

